Fleeing from Moscow
The fall of communism gave the nations of the former Soviet bloc the chance to turn towards democracy, a market economy, and the rule of law.
Some of these countries decisively broke ties with their communist past; others were less successful, and a few have catastrophically failed.
Moldova and Georgia belonged to the latter category until recently.
Their economic and political failure was largely due to secessionist movements, supported actively by Russia, which sought to keep both countries within the "sphere of influence" of the Kremlin.
As bloody conflicts erupted in Transnistria, Abkhazia, and South Ossetia, Russia transformed its military presence there into "peacekeepers" to maintain control.
For a long time, it was feared that these so-called "frozen conflicts" could suddenly turn hot.
This did not happen, however, and we can now speak of solutions – for both Georgia and Moldova have begun making progress toward market economy and democracy.
The European Union's "Neighborhood Policy" has also contributed to this.
The starting point of these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years ago.
Already dangerously close to a failed state, Georgia has now turned to the West.
The success of various "color revolutions" in former Soviet bloc countries also triggered change in Moldova. Here, President Vladimir Voronin initiated reforms aimed at rapprochement with the EU.
These changes have sparked new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova to restore the territorial integrity of these countries in a peaceful manner.
The experience of Estonia suggests how Georgia and Moldova should shape their policy towards Russia.
When Estonia became independent in 1991, Moscow sought to portray Estonia as a country with enormous economic problems that were unsuitable for investment.
Estland was indeed poor, and its main export products were scrap metal and wood, but its economy was growing.
In North-Eastern Estonia, where the majority of the population was of Russian ethnicity, who had settled there during the Soviet era, Russia supported what was called an "autonomy movement".
When Estonia resisted, Russia imposed sanctions and interrupted gas supplies.
Taxes on the few Estonian products that were allowed to be imported into Russia were high, and Russia even threatened with a military intervention.
But Estonia kept its nerve.
The Russian sanctions even helped the country to reorient its economy towards the West.
On the other hand, Western Europe did what it could to integrate the Baltic States – Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia – and at the same time tried to avoid a conflict with Russia.
In 1994, a free trade agreement with the EU enabled Estonian products to find new markets, and Estonia ultimately became one of the most successful post-communist transition countries, joining the EU and NATO in 2004.
When Georgia became independent in 1991, it was not supported in the same way by Western Europe.
Naturally, Georgia appeared less attractive as a partner than the Baltic States; the 1990s were marked by coups, counter-coups, and civil wars, during which two regions – Abkhazia and South Ossetia – largely separated with Russian support.
The country has done its best to forget its bleak past.
Since the Rose Revolution, the economy has been reformed, the army strengthened, and the leadership of the country is young, dynamic, and eagerly working to advance the nation.
Thanks to Georgia's flat income tax of 12% – likely the lowest in the world – the national budget has increased.
The government has raised pensions and increased social benefits.
Corruption is decreasing, and a judicial reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and over 10% in 2006.
Georgia is trying to defuse tensions over Abkhazia and South Ossetia; Russia, however, accuses the country of aggression as well as ethnic cleansing.
Its main goal is to prevent the West from supporting Georgia and hinder reconciliation with the breakaway regions.
The powers that matter in Georgia are Russia and to a certain extent the United States.
Europe must show that it is also important.
Estland has – during its independence and again during the recent crisis over the relocation of a World War II monument – shown that it can resist Russian pressure with determination and strong support.
Europe must understand that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Just as the free trade agreement with Europe enabled Estonia to find new markets, this could be the means by which Georgians can help themselves.
Georgia has legitimate reasons for hope that it will achieve real independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is more threatened by Russia than the Estonians or even the Georgians ever were?
The lack of reformers is partly the result of secessionist movements supported by Russia.
That industrialized region, Transnistria, which wanted closer ties to Romania – whose population speaks Russian and Ukrainian and is predominantly Moldovan of Romanian descent – broke away from Moldova at the start of its independence, delivering a heavy blow to the young country.
A civil war followed, and in 1992 Russian troops marched into Transnistria, where they remain to this day.
The independence of Transnistria was never recognized – neither by Moldova nor internationally.
It is said that there is lawlessness and corruption there.
Moldova is heavily indebted, unemployment is high, and its once-renowned wine industry is in decline.
Russia occasionally cuts off gas supplies, and many of the four million citizens have left the country.
Only Russia can solve the problem.
Representatives of Moldova have made four fruitless visits to Moscow to persuade President Vladimir Putin to take action and withdraw Russian troops.
Desperate, Voronin asked the EU observer mission Eubam for help, but an EU initiative would require Russian cooperation.
Unfortunately, it seems that the West lacks up-to-date insights into the situation in Moldova.
In April, for example, the EU and the US only learned about a proposed peace agreement through a leak in Germany.
This agreement, apparently, would benefit Russia by recognizing Transnistria as a legitimate entity within Moldova.
If Russia has thus dealt the West such a blow, it would be a ominous precedent for Georgia and other weak post-communist states.
